                            Gray-box monitoring of hyperproperties
				





Runtime verification (RV) is concerned with 
(1) generating a monitor from a formal specification Ï†, and 
(2) using the monitor to detect whether or not Ï† holds by observing events generated by the system at run time. 

Monitorability - possibility of monitoring a property. Some properties non-monitorable because no finite observation can lead to a conclusive verdict.
A formula Ï† is (semantically) monitorable if every observation O has an extended observation P â‰½ O, such that P |=s Ï† or P |=v Ï†.			s- satisfies; v- violates

âˆ€Ï€.âˆ€Ï€.î€ˆ(aÏ€ â†” Â¬aÏ€â€² ) is monitorable, but âˆ€Ï€.âˆƒÏ€.î€ˆ(aÏ€ â†” Â¬aÏ€â€² ) is not, as it requires an observation set of infinite size

A formula Ï† is seman-tically gray-box monitorable for a system S if every observation O has an extended observation P â‰½O in S, such that P |=sS Ï† or P |=vS Ï†.

Given a property Ï† and a set of behaviors S, a monitor M is sound whenever, for every observation O âˆˆ O,
1. ifO|=sS Ï†,thenM(O)=âŠ¤orM(O)=?, 
2. ifO|=vS Ï†,thenM(O)=âŠ¥orM(O)=?, 
3. otherwise M(O) = ?

Given a property Ï† and a set of traces S, a monitor M is perfect whenever, for every observation O âˆˆ O,
1. ifO|=sS Ï†thenM(O)=âŠ¤, 
2. ifO|=vS Ï†thenM(O)=âŠ¥, 
3. otherwise M(O) = ?.

A property Ï† is strongly monitorable for a system S if there is a sound monitor M s.t. for all observations O âˆˆ O, there is an extended observation P âˆˆ S for which either M(P) = âŠ¤ or M(P) = âŠ¥

if a property is not semantically monitorable, then it is not strongly monitorable but in rich domains, some semantically monitorable properties may not be strongly monitorable

If Ï† is strongly monitorable, then Ï† is semantically monitorable.
strongly monitorable => semantically monitorable
!semantically monitorable => !semantically monitorable

we propose to use a combination of static analysis and runtime verification to monitor violations of âˆ€+âˆƒ+ properties (or dually, satisfactions of âˆƒ+âˆ€+). The main idea is to collect candidates for the outer âˆƒ part dynamically and use static analysis at runtime to over-approximate the inner âˆ€ quantifiers.


(P1) DDM is not semantically black-box monitorable,
(P2) DDM is semantically white-box monitorable (for programs that are not DDM),
(P3) checking DDM statically is undecidable,
(P4) DDM is strongly gray-box monitorable for violation, and we give a sound monitor.

The static analyzer receives the finite observation O collected by the monitor, but not the future system behavior. Instead it must reason under the assumption that any system behavior in S that is compatible with O, may eventually occur.For example, given an âˆƒâˆ€ formula, the outer existential quantifier is instantiated with a concrete set U of runtime traces, while possible extensions of U provided by static analysis can be used to instantiate the inner universal quantifier.

Given a function f : I â†’ O, the problem of data minimization consists in finding a preprocessor function p: I â†’ I, such that f = f â—¦p and p = pâ—¦p. The goal of p is to limit the information available to f while preserving the behavior of f

For f : I â†’ O with finite I , Ï†dm is strongly monitorable in Sf . If I is infinite, then Ï†dm is not semantically monitorable for satisfaction, but we can still hope to build a sound monitor for violation of Ï†dm.


