Explaining Image Classifiers using Statistical Fault Localization (Explainable AI)

a black-box explanation technique based on statistical fault localization.

static fault localisation based on local perturbations

a good explanation gives an answer to the question
â€œwhy did this outcome occur

 An explanation in image classification is a minimal subset of pixels of a given input image that is sufficient for the DNN to classify the image, where â€œsufficientâ€ is defined as containing only this subset of pixels from the original image, with the other pixels set to the background colour.


"cowboy hatâ€image. Although Xception labels the input image correctly, an explanation produced by DeepCover indicates that this decision is not based on the correct feature (the hat in the image), but on the face, which is an unexpected feature for the label â€˜cowboy hatâ€™. While this image was not, technically speaking, misclassified, the explanation points to a flaw in the DNNâ€™s reasoning. 
The explanations generated by DeepCover may thus be useful for assessing the adequacy of the DNN training: they allow us to check, whether the DNN is aligned with the developerâ€™s intent during training.
a DNN is â€œtrojanedâ€ if it behaves correctly on ordinary input images but exhibits malicious behavior when a â€œTrojan triggerâ€ is part of the input.


